# {{PROJECT_NAME}} — Access Revocation Runbook

> **This is a starting-point template, not legal advice.** Adapt the
> systems, tier thresholds, and notification flow to your organization
> before relying on this for an actual termination or role-change event.

**Profile**: `{{COMPLIANCE_PROFILE}}` · **Owner**: `[fill in: role]` ·
**Last updated**: `[fill in: YYYY-MM-DD]`

## When to invoke

- A team member or contractor leaves the organization (planned or
  immediate).
- A team member's role changes such that they should no longer have
  access to a system they previously did.
- A vendor or third-party integration is terminated.
- A credential is suspected of compromise (also see
  [`../docs/compliance/breach-response.md`](../docs/compliance/breach-response.md)
  Phase 3 — Contain).

## Tier classification

Access tiers determine SLA targets:

| Tier | Examples | SLA target |
|---|---|---|
| **Critical** | Production secrets, root cloud accounts, database admin. | ≤ 1 hour from trigger. |
| **Elevated** | Production application accounts, customer-data access, deployment pipelines. | ≤ 4 hours from trigger. |
| **Standard** | Development environments, internal-tool accounts, document repositories. | ≤ 24 hours from trigger. |
| **Reference-only** | Read-only docs, archived systems. | ≤ 72 hours from trigger. |

For a suspected compromise, all tiers compress to "immediate."

## Steps

### 1. Identify scope (≤ 30 minutes from trigger)

- Identify the person + reason for revocation.
- Enumerate the systems and roles to be revoked (use the access
  matrix at `[fill in: where your access matrix lives]`).
- Identify any in-flight work that needs reassignment.
- Identify any vendor credentials issued to or under control of the
  person.

### 2. Revoke credentials (per tier SLA)

Order: highest tier first.

- **Identity provider**: disable the account at the SSO / IdP layer
  first — this cascades to most other systems.
- **Direct vendor accounts** without SSO: revoke individually.
- **API tokens / service accounts** owned by the person: rotate or
  revoke. If shared with the team, rotate and redistribute.
- **Local credentials**: where applicable, recover devices and
  remove cached credentials.

### 3. Invalidate active sessions

- Force-logout active sessions in each system that supports it.
- Revoke OAuth grants the person had authorized.
- Revoke long-lived browser cookies / "remember me" tokens.

### 4. Audit-log the action

For each revocation, write an audit event capturing:

- Actor performing the revocation.
- Subject (person whose access is being revoked).
- Trigger reason.
- Tier + system + role.
- Timestamp.
- Confirmation that the action was successful (or the failure to
  follow up on).

This is the evidence trail required for PIPEDA Principle 1
(Accountability) and Principle 7 (Safeguards) — see
[`../docs/compliance/audit-log-requirements.md`](../docs/compliance/audit-log-requirements.md).

### 5. Reassign and follow up

- Reassign any in-flight work to a current team member.
- Update CODEOWNERS / on-call schedules / paging rotations.
- Update the access matrix (entries owned by the person are removed
  or transferred).
- Update subprocessor entries if the person was the named contact for
  any vendor relationship.

### 6. Notify (where applicable)

- For role-changes: notify the affected person and their manager that
  the change is complete.
- For terminations: notify the team per your internal communications
  policy.
- For suspected compromise: do **not** notify the affected person until
  legal counsel confirms — that's an active investigation in the
  containment phase of breach response.

## Failure modes

- A system has no SSO and was missed in step 2 → maintain the access
  matrix as a comprehensive list; audit it quarterly.
- A vendor credential was on a personal device → recover the device
  before separation; otherwise rotate the credential.
- An OAuth grant cannot be revoked centrally → document this in the
  access matrix as a "manual revocation required" entry so it gets
  caught.

## Verification (within 24 hours of completion)

- [ ] Re-attempt login as the revoked identity at the SSO layer.
      Expectation: fail.
- [ ] Spot-check 3 critical-tier systems for any active session.
      Expectation: none.
- [ ] Spot-check any API token the person was known to own.
      Expectation: rejected.
- [ ] Audit log shows the revocation actions.

